      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The perceived \"regressive tax\" argument is a massive political hurdle that needs to be overcome with smart policy design, not by abandoning the tool. Planners reconcile this by coupling congestion pricing with robust transit improvements and targeted rebates for low-income residents. The long-term environmental and public health benefits of cleaner air and less gridlock are ultimately what drive the necessity, making the upfront economic adjustment a necessary investment in a functional city.",
